| Philosophy | Socrates, who taught in the Agora |

## Athens as the School of Greece

Pericles called Athens "the school of Hellas" — and the claim was not empty boasting. The philosophical tradition born in Athens:

- **Socrates** (470–399 BC) developed the art of questioning — the Socratic method — as the path to wisdom and self-knowledge. He was executed for allegedly corrupting Athenian youth and impiety, dying with serenity that impressed even his enemies.
- **Plato** (428–348 BC) founded the Academy and developed the theory of Forms, articulating the first systematic philosophy of knowledge, reality, politics, and the soul.
- **Aristotle** (384–322 BC) studied at Plato's Academy, then founded his own school, the Lyceum. His work in logic, ethics, biology, physics, and metaphysics established the categories of inquiry still used in universities today.

## The Acropolis

The Acropolis ("high city") was the sacred center of Athens — a limestone hill topped by temples to the Olympian gods. The Parthenon, built 447–432 BC, honored the city's patron goddess Athena and housed a magnificent chryselephantine (gold and ivory) statue of her.

The Acropolis remains one of the world's most significant archaeological sites and a symbol of Western civilization's intellectual and artistic heritage.

## The Agora

The Agora was Athens's civic and commercial center — a large open space at the foot of the Acropolis surrounded by temples, stoas (colonnaded porches), and government buildings. It was here that Athenian democracy functioned, traders conducted business, and philosophers like Socrates debated in public.

Paul the Apostle preached in the Athenian Agora (Acts 17:17) during his missionary journeys, famously addressing the Areopagus: "Men of Athens, I perceive that in every way you are very religious" — noting an altar inscribed "To an Unknown God" and using it to proclaim the resurrected Christ.

## Decline

Athens suffered a catastrophic defeat at Syracuse in Sicily (413 BC), the turning point in the Peloponnesian War against Sparta. Though Athens recovered somewhat, it never regained its political supremacy. Macedonia under Philip II and then Alexander the Great eclipsed the independent city-states of Greece.

## Legacy

The ideas born in Athens — democracy, rational inquiry, philosophy, drama — form the bedrock of Western civilization. Modern law, science, literature, and political thought trace their lineage to this small city in the eastern Mediterranean. The very vocabulary of Western intellectual life is largely Greek.

